00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.000
to say what is tinymobiles.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
So it is

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
the framework for

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
statistical modeling and machine

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
learning in R.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.000
And it is a framework that

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
uses tinyverse principles. So the

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
same ideas

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.000
that

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:20.000
have been used in tinyverse

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.000
are now being learned and used

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
in design ideas of how

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:26.000
functions

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
should work, how you should be able to

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.000
interact with them.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
All of these things that have made the tinyverse

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:34.000
popular are the same design

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.000
ideas that we try

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
to apply to

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:40.000
what I consider the heart

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
of our modeling statistics.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
It's still sort of like

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
the crafting base.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.000
And

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:50.000
essentially if you

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.000
feel at home with the tinyverse,

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
you should feel at home with tinymobiles

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.000
as well.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:58.000
And when I got

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:00.000
asked to talk about what is new,

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
the usual interpretation of

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
what is new is

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:06.000
what is new and has been

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:08.000
released.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:10.000
And I'm going to be talking about this,

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.000
but I'm going to be talking about this

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
more

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
briefly than the second part

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:18.000
here, which is what is new and in

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.000
progress. So you're getting a little bit of

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:22.000
work in progress.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.000
And part of the reason

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.000
why I've decided to

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:28.000
keep new and released

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
a little bit more contained here is

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
that we

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:34.000
most of these big releases

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:36.000
of the year happened in the first half of

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.000
the year, and then we talked about them

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:40.000
in various places.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:42.000
Amongst them,

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.000
PositCons in August,

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.000
and the talk videos

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
from PositCons are now online since last

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
week. So they're all on YouTube,

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
including ours. We had a session

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
of tinymodels talks

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
with plenty of others,

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.000
and I do believe that

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.000
the quality of these talks

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.000
at PositCons was really good.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.000
So if you're curious, I

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
encourage you to go check out those videos,

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:08.000
and I'll give you

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:10.000
sort of like a pull-out,

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.000
a tinymodels session.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
In a minute, you can decide whether

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
that's of your interest or if you want to

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
try some other ones.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
So

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.000
the thing that probably

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:24.000
took the longest out of these releases

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:26.000
is adding support

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
for timed event data to

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:30.000
the entire framework.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
So timed event data,

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.000
as the name suggests,

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.000
has like two

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
aspects of it. The timed

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.000
event and the event itself.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:42.000
And that event may or may not

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.000
have happened yet when you're like,

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
but I don't want to analyze stuff.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.000
If it hasn't happened,

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
that's a censored observation.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
It's not a missing observation. It's incomplete.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
But you still want to make use

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:56.000
of that data.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
So

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:00.000
for the stats people in the room,

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:02.000
it's pretty obvious that the methodology

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.000
to deal with both

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.000
an outcome that has

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.000
two aspects, and there's

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
something involved. This methodology

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.000
is survival analysis.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.000
For people who are not so familiar with

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.000
this, the name survival

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
analysis usually does something

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
that's a circle like medical

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.000
research and that's not applicable to

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.000
me. And I've been trying to tell

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:26.000
people this year in particular

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.000
that it's timed event

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
data and then methodology

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.000
for that. And that event can be really

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
a lot of things. Yes, it can be data

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:36.000
in a medical context, but it can also

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
be like time until

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
your pet gets adopted in the shelter.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
So pretty broad applications

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:44.000
and

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:46.000
we've wired

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:48.000
our support for it throughout the framework

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
with

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
its own mode,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
regression,

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.000
and I got to talk

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.000
about

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
the general why

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:02.000
and what

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:04.000
in more of an introductory

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
talk

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
on data and models.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
And then that's it.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.000
A follow up talk right after me

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.000
talking about how to measure

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:16.000
predictive performance for these types

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
of models.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
So if that is data you may

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
encounter and you want to use

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
tiny models, these are the two talks to check out.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
My colleague Simon

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
talked about a very different topic.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:32.000
He talked about fair machine

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:34.000
learning.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
And the tiny models does include

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
several metrics

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.000
for fair machine learning.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
And there isn't like one

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:44.000
silver bullet, one metric

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.000
that answers all your questions

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
because

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
there just isn't one. So we also

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
did not try to implement one.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.000
But rather

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:56.000
Simon and other colleagues at Posit

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.000
spent

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:00.000
almost a year, I think, sort of catching up on

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
literature on other

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
implementations and then deciding on

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
what to implement for tiny models.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
And they've chosen it

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
to have metrics that

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
support you when you're thinking about

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
a problem rather than

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:16.000
presenting you a

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:18.000
too easy and not

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.000
real solution.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:22.000
And he does a really nice job in situating

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.000
that research

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
and questions

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
in his talk on fair machine learning.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
And last

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
but not least

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
is Emile's work

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
on making

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
predictions happen in databases.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.000
So if you're working

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
in a context where you make

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
AI a model and you have

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.000
loads of data in your database,

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
it's nice

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
to not have to pull that data

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.000
into R to make a prediction and then

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
write it in R, but that you can

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.000
do it in your database first.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
And that is

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.000
what the tiny predict package

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
was doing, but it was doing it

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
for a personal model.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:08.000
So in the easy

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:10.000
case, if you have a linear

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
model, you know your coefficients, you can

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.000
write a SQL or other

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
expression that

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.000
multiplies your vector coefficients

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
with your predictor values, and you

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
get your prediction.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
And that can happen on a database.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.000
But that wasn't including

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
any of the preprocessing.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.000
And Emile has gone through the work of

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.000
trying to make this work for

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:36.000
tiny models of workflows

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.000
so the objects can include preprocessing

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:40.000
and the fitted model.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.000
The package is called

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:44.000
Orbital if you want to check

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
it out, and the talk is also

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
linked in the slides. My slides are

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
online. I'm not sure if you can read

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:52.000
it, but they're on my GitHub.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.000
You know, get my GitHub profile.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.000
It's just a trick.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.000
I'm sure you'll find it, but

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
it's sort of the retro 2024

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
dash 3 RPR.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
So that is what

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
we've been working on earlier in the

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
year. That is our

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
desktop videos and blog posts and whatnot.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
If any of this

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
catches your fancy, go check it out.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.000
And I'm

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:20.000
going to very smoothly segue

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.000
into the new

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
vision in progress. Some things get

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.000
a lot more...

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.000
less polished. Let's put it that way.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.000
And the

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
first thing I want to talk about in that

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:34.000
moment where we're actively working on

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:36.000
things is the topic of

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.000
post-processing.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:40.000
And I've decided to slap the

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
subtitle on. That's what

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.000
you do after you've done fitting your model.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:46.000
And you do it to your model predictions, not

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.000
to your data.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
The reason usually

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.000
being you're trying to squeeze a little bit

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
more performance out of it, trying to make

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.000
the predictions better after you

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
figure out how to make the predictions.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:02.000
But let's look at an example.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:04.000
So I brought some delivery

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.000
data. That's just how long it takes

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:08.000
to get something delivered.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.000
Since I talked about censored data earlier,

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:12.000
this is all uncensored.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:14.000
This is the actual time until the event.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
Just looking at the time now, we're keeping

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
things easy in this example.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
So time to

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
delivery is our response. We've got

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:24.000
a couple of predictors. We're doing

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:26.000
the usual tiny models thing

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.000
where we split it and try to do testing.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.000
And we're also preparing

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:32.000
something for 10-fold cross-validation.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:34.000
And then

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:36.000
we're going to pick a model, and I'm going to

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:38.000
deliberately make the model really

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:40.000
bad to show you why

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
you might want to test your predictions.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:44.000
So this is a

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
boosted tree

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.000
with a glorious number

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
of three trees. So you're

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.000
not going to get something very

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.000
performant, but you get a model.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
We're not doing any pre-processing

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.000
on the predictors. We are just showing it straight.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.000
We're going to resample

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.000
that model, put it on the

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
10-fold cross-validation.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
We're going to get some metrics

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.000
out of that, and we are going to

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.000
save those predictions.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.000
We have metrics, so we might as well look at them.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.000
And we get

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.000
an R-squared

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.000
of like 0.8

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.000
something, which is not too terrible.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:32.000
But as always,

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:34.000
you've got to remember what

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.000
your metric is actually measuring.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
And R-squared makes the correlation.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
It doesn't tell you

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.000
how close your prediction

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.000
is to your observed value.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.000
That is a different topic. It's calibration.

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:50.000
Why not look at it as a thought?

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
This is done

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
with the probably package.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.000
You can see

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
that for

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
higher actual observed values,

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.000
the model

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:08.000
quite severely under-predicts

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.000
them.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.000
This is not a new model.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:14.000
I mean, deliberately so, but

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.000
if you're trying your hardest to get a good model

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
and that's your result,

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:22.000
things are challenging.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:24.000
And one of the things that

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:26.000
you can do with this is calibration,

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:28.000
and that's what we're going to be doing.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:32.000
Generally, why would you want

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:34.000
to do any of the post-processing?

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:36.000
Usually the motivation

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
is to get better

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:40.000
predictions out of it

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:42.000
with sort of adding a

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.000
hit-stack, and calibration is another model

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:46.000
on top of that.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:48.000
Or sometimes you simply want to

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:50.000
better satisfy

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:52.000
distributional limitations.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:54.000
You might have a range that

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:56.000
your predictions can't be outside of,

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:58.000
something similar.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:00.000
And currently,

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:02.000
you can

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:04.000
do that, and things keep moving from it.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
It is not necessarily the

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.000
immediate way.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:12.000
You can just do straight-up

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.000
decline manipulations

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:16.000
on it, if you're just

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:18.000
thresholding predictive

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:20.000
probabilities into hard classes

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:22.000
with something other than 0.5.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:26.000
Or you could use the PROBABLY package

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:28.000
which has calibration compliments

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.000
in it, from America.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.000
That is all okay,

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
but what we are

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:38.000
now doing is integrating it

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:40.000
into the workflows objects.

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:42.000
So a workflow

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.000
in kaiju models is the thing

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:46.000
that contains, currently,

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:48.000
your pre-processing

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:50.000
instructions

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:52.000
and your model instructions.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:54.000
The idea being that putting them together

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:56.000
makes it easy to cross-validate

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:58.000
them together, and you're not

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:00.000
creating

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:02.000
data that you can pre-process.

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:04.000
Now we are adding

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:06.000
post-processing

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:08.000
to go into that object,

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:10.000
so that you can

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:12.000
fit the whole thing.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:14.000
Do fit-me samples

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:16.000
on the whole thing.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:20.000
We have a new

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.000
package on the block

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:24.000
for that kind of stuff.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:26.000
Meet Taylor.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:28.000
So,

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:30.000
the Taylor package is the thing

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:32.000
that connects

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:36.000
stuff in PROBABLY

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:38.000
and DeFi, so to say,

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:40.000
with the workflow.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:46.000
If you think of recipes

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:48.000
for pre-processing,

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:50.000
think of Taylor

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:52.000
for post-processing.

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:54.000
That's the mental model

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:56.000
that we're borrowing from.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:58.000
If you have one for recipes,

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:00.000
you're a good bit of the way there

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:02.000
for Taylor.

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:06.000
Similarities

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:08.000
and differences in that mental model.

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:10.000
Recipes

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:12.000
works on the training data

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:14.000
because we're doing pre-processing.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:16.000
Taylor works on the model predictions

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:18.000
because we're doing post-processing.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:20.000
But you both

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:22.000
initialize an object

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:24.000
for recipes and services,

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:26.000
and then you add

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.000
more specifications

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:30.000
to it. Steps to do.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:32.000
Recipe steps.

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:34.000
And in Taylor, those steps

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:36.000
are adjustments to do.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:40.000
And then you sort of have

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:42.000
not only the nature's fault.

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:44.000
There's nothing more, just dead space.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:50.000
And then you have a part where you

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:52.000
estimate something.

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:54.000
And then the part where you

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:56.000
execute some things, often

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:58.000
false predict. And there are false fit

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:00.000
and predict for Taylor.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:02.000
I assume you're

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.000
somewhat familiar with recipes, so

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:06.000
that is the

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:08.000
corresponding parts to practice it.

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:10.000
I think those are

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:12.000
harder to learn than fit and predict.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.000
But that is

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:18.000
a very brief intro

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:20.000
to Taylor.

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:22.000
And let's use it.

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:24.000
Let's use it in the workbook.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:26.000
We need to call library

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:28.000
Taylor. Nothing happens with that.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:30.000
But then

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:32.000
we can make a Taylor object.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:34.000
We initialize it with call to Taylor

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:36.000
like we would with recipe.

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:38.000
Recipe. Brackets up

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:40.000
and close. And then we're

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:42.000
adding the additional

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:44.000
instructions of what to do with our model

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:46.000
predictions. In this case

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:48.000
here, I'm adding an adjustment that

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:50.000
is a numeric calibration.

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:52.000
So that's off the

00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:54.000
wall predictions.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:56.000
You're going to get calibrated.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:58.000
And

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:00.000
we have this Taylor object

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:02.000
that I knew would have a recipe object.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:04.000
And like we would

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:06.000
add a recipe to a

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:08.000
workflow with the add recipe function,

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:10.000
there is now also a

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:12.000
add Taylor function.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:14.000
So

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:16.000
hopefully all of your

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:18.000
intimidations that you've

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:20.000
built up with tiny models already

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:22.000
are working and

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:24.000
you can be like, yeah, I'm mapping this knowledge

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:26.000
to a new part.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:28.000
So we can

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:30.000
add the Taylor here. And now we have

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.000
a workflow that has instructions

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:34.000
for pre-processing, for the model fit,

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:36.000
and for post-processing.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:38.000
And then we can send that thing through

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:40.000
fit resamples, like we

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:42.000
did before. The only

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:44.000
thing that's changed here is the object

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:46.000
that goes into it.

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:48.000
We're still saving the predictions

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:50.000
so that I can do the original

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:52.000
plot.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:54.000
And you can see, still

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:56.000
not perfect, but we're

00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:58.000
getting closer to that diagonal line.

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:00.000
Still struggling with

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:02.000
predictions for large

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:04.000
observed values,

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:06.000
but we're getting

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:08.000
it.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:10.000
So

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:12.000
success.

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:14.000
I

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:16.000
think this is work in progress, so let's talk

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:18.000
about what it can do and what

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:20.000
it can't do yet.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:22.000
So what is implemented

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:24.000
in Taylor as options

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:26.000
for post-processing

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:28.000
is

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:30.000
what we expect to be

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:32.000
the

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.000
most useful and commonly

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:36.000
requested ones.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:38.000
So if you

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:40.000
have something that you need that's not

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:42.000
on this list, I will show the site

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:44.000
where to get the feedback. Let us know.

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:46.000
But we're hoping we're covering a lot of

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.000
bases with this already.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:50.000
You can calibrate

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:52.000
probabilities. You

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:54.000
can

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:56.000
either pick a different threshold

00:25:56.000 --> 00:25:58.000
or use equivocal signs

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.000
if you're turning your probabilities

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:02.000
into hard class predictions.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:04.000
And for numeric outcomes,

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:06.000
you can calibrate them

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:08.000
or tweak the range.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:11.000
And

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:13.000
we have implemented both

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:15.000
Taylor itself.

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:17.000
There's support for it in

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:19.000
workflows, so that you can say

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:21.000
add Taylor.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:23.000
And as you've seen,

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:25.000
fit with samples and tune works

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:27.000
with this already.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:29.000
And then there's like this unassuming line

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:31.000
of support for our sample

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:33.000
for sundry samples.

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:35.000
That concerns calibration. So calibration

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:37.000
essentially fits another model

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:39.000
on your model predictions

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:41.000
as an input

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:43.000
and your true

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:45.000
outcome as an outcome.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:47.000
And if you fit yet another

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:49.000
model,

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:51.000
you want fresh

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:53.000
data, unseen data.

00:26:53.000 --> 00:26:55.000
You don't

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:57.000
want to risk overfitting

00:26:57.000 --> 00:26:59.000
by just adding a model on top of a model

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:01.000
on top of a model

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:03.000
and fine tuning too much

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:05.000
on each range of data. So what

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:07.000
happens underneath the hood is

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:09.000
that we hold back some of your

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:11.000
training data for calibration

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:13.000
if you have told us in your

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:15.000
specification that that is what you want

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:17.000
to be doing.

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:19.000
And how we do that

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:21.000
is implemented in our sample

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:23.000
and we have that for

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:25.000
cross-validation

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:27.000
and booster

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:29.000
samples and

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:31.000
there are some more to go

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:33.000
including temporal

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:35.000
datasets.

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:37.000
And

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:39.000
yeah, sort of

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:41.000
that is part

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:43.000
of what's yet to come.

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:45.000
And

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:47.000
the other thing that we still need

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:49.000
to wire up in this

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:51.000
is that you can

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:53.000
tune with all

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:55.000
of TUNE and not just say fit pre-samples

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:57.000
but you could say TUNE

00:27:57.000 --> 00:27:59.000
on a workflow that has pre-processing

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:01.000
on specification and

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:03.000
pre-processing info.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:05.000
And if you

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:07.000
care about this topic

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:09.000
and want to give us feedback

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:11.000
that is very welcome.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:13.000
The best place to do this is

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:15.000
by issues

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:17.000
on GitHub on

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:19.000
the Taylor repository.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:21.000
So in the tidy models

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:23.000
or on GitHub is the Taylor repository

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:25.000
if you've got issues

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:27.000
leave us your feedback there.

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:29.000
Um

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:31.000
yeah

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:33.000
so that is one

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:35.000
thing that is work in progress

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:37.000
that is in the pipeline.

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:39.000
It's not too far off I would say

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:41.000
and we're

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:43.000
just going to move

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:45.000
a little further.

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:47.000
The other topic that's

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:49.000
sort of hooking in the tidy models section

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:51.000
is support

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:53.000
for sparsity

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:55.000
in a better way than currently.

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:57.000
What I

00:28:57.000 --> 00:28:59.000
call sparse tables

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:01.000
and

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:03.000
um

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:05.000
sparse data in the wild

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:07.000
would be

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:09.000
something you encounter

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:11.000
if you have

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:13.000
categorical predictors with a lot

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:15.000
of categories and you turn those into

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:17.000
indicators or you

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:19.000
tokenize text or you have a graph

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:21.000
data set. You can easily

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:23.000
end up with

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:25.000
a lot of variables

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:27.000
and then a lot of zeros

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:29.000
in them. So like the

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:31.000
information in your data

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:33.000
is pretty sparse

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:35.000
in that context. And people

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:37.000
often shorten it down to like

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:39.000
sparse data. So that's

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:41.000
where the slogan or the name

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:43.000
comes from. And having a

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:45.000
lot of data

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:47.000
with a lot of zeros

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:49.000
instead of like

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:51.000
going from one column of

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:53.000
a categorical

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:55.000
variable to like multiple,

00:29:55.000 --> 00:29:57.000
multiple columns

00:29:57.000 --> 00:29:59.000
can sometimes be a challenge in two terms.

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:01.000
One, memory

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:03.000
allocation. Your data set

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:05.000
is already big and then you can like turn one

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:07.000
column into many, many.

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:09.000
That's not always

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:11.000
easy. And the other thing

00:30:11.000 --> 00:30:13.000
is speed.

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:15.000
Because you need to work with

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:17.000
each other.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:19.000
And

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:21.000
the way that this is typically addressed is

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:23.000
a different data

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:25.000
representation.

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:27.000
Different to

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:29.000
what? Is a solid question.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:31.000
So the fault

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:33.000
is called a dense representation.

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:35.000
We have a vector like this

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:37.000
and we store all

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:39.000
of the 25 values.

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:41.000
That's a dense representation.

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:43.000
I don't need

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:45.000
you to count the zeros, but you probably

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:47.000
have spotted

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:49.000
the non-zero values because they're

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:51.000
only two.

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:53.000
So if we don't want to store

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:55.000
all 25 of them,

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:57.000
because these two are the things that really

00:30:57.000 --> 00:30:59.000
interest us, we can

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:01.000
try to switch to

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:03.000
a sparse representation.

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:05.000
And we only need five of these for that.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:07.000
So we need to remember how long

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:09.000
that vector is.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:11.000
So that's one for the 25.

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:13.000
We need to

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:15.000
save the locations

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:17.000
for the non-zero values.

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:19.000
That's another two here.

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:21.000
And we need to save those non-zero values

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:23.000
themselves.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:25.000
So another two.

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:27.000
But I'm five versus the 25.

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:29.000
And whether that's an interesting loop

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:31.000
depends on how sparse your data is.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:33.000
There isn't like, this is always better.

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:35.000
I think we all know that's no free lunch,

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:37.000
right?

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:39.000
There is a little bit of a trade-off,

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:41.000
but if you are in a situation

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:43.000
where you do encounter a lot of zeros, it's interesting.

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:45.000
In

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:47.000
this complete layer, in R,

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:49.000
we're implementing stuff.

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:51.000
This is called matrix

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:53.000
packet, with a capital M,

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:55.000
that implements sparse matrices

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:57.000
and

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:59.000
sparse vectors

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:01.000
in efficient matrix operations for this.

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:03.000
So we're addressing both the memory

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:05.000
return and the speed.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:07.000
And you can make a sparse vector.

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:09.000
I made the one

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:11.000
that I just showed you,

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:13.000
with the 25 values and two non-zeros.

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:15.000
Again,

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:17.000
even a great method looks pretty sparse,

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:19.000
right?

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:21.000
And

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:23.000
matrices

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:25.000
are

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:27.000
good

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:29.000
when you're really close

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:31.000
to knowing if it's

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:33.000
a model, when you

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:35.000
actually have a model matrix.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:37.000
And

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:39.000
the

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:41.000
efficient matrix

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:43.000
operations are for that.

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:47.000
But that's pretty late in the game.

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:49.000
Usually when you have

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:51.000
a data,

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:53.000
you have it in a data frame

00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:55.000
for a good reason, because you have

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:57.000
often different types of data, right?

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:03.000
So

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:05.000
there's a little bit of a hiccup

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:07.000
in using the matrix

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:09.000
package directly in

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:11.000
the high-resonance framework.

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:13.000
So if you give us

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:15.000
such a matrix to go fit

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:17.000
the model, we can take it and pass

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:19.000
it on to the modeling function. We're not crunching

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:21.000
it, it's fine. That is what is there already.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:25.000
But we have a slight problem

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:27.000
trying to stick sparsity

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:29.000
into tuples.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:35.000
I feel like in these sort of things

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:37.000
it's always good to remember,

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:39.000
what are you trying to do, what are you trying

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:41.000
not to do, and why?

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:43.000
And the best place to start is

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:45.000
why. So

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:47.000
let's pull back for a moment and

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:49.000
talk about what

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:51.000
we would really like to have here.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:53.000
Simple one,

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:55.000
if you have

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:57.000
something that isn't a sparse data format,

00:33:57.000 --> 00:33:59.000
we would like to preserve that

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:01.000
throughout the framework.

00:34:03.000 --> 00:34:05.000
If you run into something that's

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:07.000
concave or sparse data,

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:09.000
they will materialize and fall

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:11.000
back to the bench representation.

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:19.000
We want to preserve it

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:21.000
and

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:23.000
we want to preserve it across the framework.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:25.000
And the thing that carries

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:27.000
data across IE models

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:29.000
is a tuple.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:31.000
That's where my interest for

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:33.000
putting a sparse vector into

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:35.000
a tuple comes from.

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:37.000
The other thing we would

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:39.000
like to have

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:41.000
is to be able to

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:43.000
make use of sparsity

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:45.000
where it makes sense.

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:47.000
Maybe if you're

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:49.000
turning your categorical variable

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:51.000
into a lot of

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:53.000
indicator variables, you want to

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:55.000
make use of them and you want to make sparse

00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:57.000
indicator variables.

00:34:57.000 --> 00:34:59.000
That's where we would like to be able to

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:01.000
add sparsity.

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:03.000
But note that this

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:05.000
is

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:07.000
sparsity on a prediction of

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:09.000
or in terms of objects,

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:11.000
we want actually sparse

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:13.000
vectors and we

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:15.000
want them in a tuple.

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:17.000
And

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:19.000
the last one is

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:21.000
kind of casual, like we want to make things

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:23.000
easy.

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:25.000
Sounds great, but it really

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:27.000
is like a fundamental idea of

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:29.000
all of

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:31.000
models. The idea of always being

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:33.000
not

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:35.000
easy for easy, say, but

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:37.000
rather if you're dealing with compressed problems,

00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:39.000
we

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:41.000
don't want you to spend all

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:43.000
your energy and making capability

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:45.000
on the

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:47.000
technical bits of handling sparsity.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:49.000
We want you to be

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:51.000
able to rely on value models for that

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:53.000
and keep your focus on the

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:55.000
actual modeling.

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:57.000
So that's why this matters.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:35:59.000
And

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:01.000
we want you to not sit

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:03.000
like, as a small example, we don't

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:05.000
want you to be like, oh, but I actually

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:07.000
don't need all of the rows and the

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:09.000
fills of this.

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:11.000
Will it break sparsity

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:13.000
if I take out some rows

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:15.000
because it's not going to change anything?

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:17.000
You just want to be able

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:19.000
to say dply or mutator

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:21.000
or dply or filter.

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:23.000
You do probably. We certainly

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:25.000
do.

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:27.000
That is a long-winded way of

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:29.000
saying why

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:31.000
do you really want

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:33.000
sparse vectors in a

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:35.000
tuple? Not all of them have

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:37.000
to be sparse, but we want to be able to have

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:39.000
some vectors to be sparse.

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:41.000
And

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:43.000
as you saw, unfortunately

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:45.000
we can't just straight up

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:47.000
stick sparse vectors

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:49.000
from the matrix, capital M,

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:51.000
package into a tuple.

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:53.000
For technical reasons, I'm not going

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:55.000
to dive into,

00:36:55.000 --> 00:36:57.000
but you're going to be like,

00:36:57.000 --> 00:36:59.000
welcome sparse vectors.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:01.000
So

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:03.000
that is another moment of

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:05.000
what are we doing, what are we not

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:07.000
doing? So sparse vectors

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:09.000
is not intended as a

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:11.000
replacement for the matrix package.

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:13.000
It is our way to have

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:15.000
sparse vectors that we can

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:17.000
stick into tuples

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:19.000
and we're not aiming to

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:21.000
implement any of the efficient

00:37:21.000 --> 00:37:23.000
matrix operations that the matrix

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:25.000
package has. So if that's

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:27.000
what you're interested in, then

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:29.000
go to the

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:31.000
matrix package for matrix operations.

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:33.000
That said,

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:35.000
sparse vectors is

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:37.000
its own package,

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:39.000
and if that sounds interesting to you,

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:41.000
you can go use it.

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:43.000
We won't use it, or we are

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:45.000
using it in tidy models, but it's its own thing

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:47.000
and you can use it in other

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:49.000
contexts if that fits to you.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:51.000
So it

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:53.000
allows us to do that thing that I was

00:37:53.000 --> 00:37:55.000
after, put sparse vectors

00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:57.000
into tuples,

00:37:57.000 --> 00:37:59.000
and because we want to be able

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:01.000
to talk with the rest of the world, also

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:03.000
it has fast conversion methods

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:05.000
to go from a tuple

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:07.000
with a sparse vector in it to

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:09.000
formats of

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:11.000
the capital and the matrix package

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:13.000
so that you can then

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:15.000
send that to

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:17.000
a model fitting function, for example.

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:19.000
Okay,

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:21.000
I said work in progress,

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:23.000
I said some stuff's implemented,

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:25.000
some stuff's not, so let's get to that part.

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:27.000
Implemented already

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:29.000
in recipes

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:31.000
is that

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:33.000
the server of everything in recipes,

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:35.000
the recipe function itself,

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:37.000
knows what to do with this

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:39.000
and doesn't just smash it first

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:41.000
and then materialize it.

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:43.000
So that will

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:45.000
pass through.

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:47.000
That will pass through.

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:49.000
It will also pass through prep and bake.

00:38:51.000 --> 00:38:53.000
Parsing's fitXY function

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:55.000
also does not

00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:57.000
store its sparsity,

00:38:57.000 --> 00:38:59.000
neither does predict.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:01.000
And in workflows,

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:03.000
fit and predict also

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:05.000
leave us alone.

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:07.000
Which is really nice.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:09.000
But obviously,

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:11.000
what's not happening?

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:13.000
So there's currently

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:15.000
Well,

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:17.000
I could say a caveat, but

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:19.000
really it's like the area where the work

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:21.000
is at right now

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:23.000
are the recipe steps.

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:25.000
So,

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:27.000
whether

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:29.000
a step touches a sparse

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:31.000
predictor,

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:33.000
it may or may not be sparse at least.

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:35.000
So for some steps,

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:37.000
that's just

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:39.000
inherent to what you do. Like if you're

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:41.000
sticking a vector into a PCA,

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:43.000
you're not having something sparse there.

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:45.000
And you will not

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:47.000
But if you're doing sort of like the

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:49.000
indicator variables,

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:51.000
or other things where it might

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:53.000
make sense to keep sparsity,

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:55.000
the goal is to preserve that.

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:57.000
And some of them work already and some of them don't.

00:39:57.000 --> 00:39:59.000
So whether or not

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:01.000
the data

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:03.000
set that you get found at the end of

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:05.000
your recipe preprocessing is

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:07.000
still sparse

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:09.000
has the answer. It depends. And it depends

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:11.000
on what kind of steps you're doing.

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:13.000
And then,

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:15.000
there is

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:17.000
one thing that some people want to

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:19.000
do, and some people are skeptical about,

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:21.000
which is why I put a big

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:23.000
baby on this.

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:25.000
So if you want to use a formula

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:27.000
interface, which is lovely,

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:29.000
which is a great thing about R,

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:31.000
and in

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:33.000
tidy models, that is

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:35.000
sort of called fit

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:37.000
on a participant model,

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:39.000
or if you

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:41.000
invoke that by app, using app

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:43.000
formulas as the

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:45.000
preprocessor in your workflow,

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:47.000
then you're down on code

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:49.000
paths that will eventually lead you

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:51.000
to model.matrix from base R.

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:53.000
And that one

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:55.000
uses dense data.

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:57.000
And

00:40:57.000 --> 00:40:59.000
unless we

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:01.000
write something that

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:03.000
replaces model.matrix,

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:05.000
that will

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:07.000
be the case.

00:41:07.000 --> 00:41:09.000
So maybe

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:11.000
we will have this in special cases.

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:13.000
It will, I'm pretty

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:15.000
sure it will not be a

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:17.000
it will always work kind of

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:19.000
situation because of the nature

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:21.000
of things.

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:23.000
But I don't want to send you

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:25.000
off to the side like,

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:27.000
it's not going to happen.

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:29.000
This

00:41:29.000 --> 00:41:31.000
is very much a work in progress.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:33.000
But we are pretty excited

00:41:33.000 --> 00:41:35.000
about this because of the

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:37.000
possibilities that this opens up

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:39.000
for sparsity in

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:41.000
preprocessing

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:43.000
maybe.

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:45.000
So far, sparsity

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:47.000
is mainly relevant for model

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:49.000
fitting, and now

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:51.000
there's more happening

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:53.000
on the preprocessing side.

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:55.000
So we don't quite

00:41:55.000 --> 00:41:57.000
know yet where that will lead us, but we're pretty excited

00:41:57.000 --> 00:41:59.000
to find out.

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:01.000
This is the feedback side.

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:03.000
If you have feedback on sparsity

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:05.000
in general, and sparse vectors

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:07.000
in particular,

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:09.000
put the issue

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:11.000
with the sparse vectors

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:13.000
repository. That is not

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:15.000
under tidy models, that is under

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:17.000
Erlang.

00:42:17.000 --> 00:42:19.000
Presumably if you search it, you'll find it.

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:21.000
If you have

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:23.000
feedback on sparsity

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:25.000
in context,

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:27.000
go to the corresponding

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:29.000
repository, so if it's sparsity

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:31.000
in preprocessing, go to

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:33.000
this. Leave us a note

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:35.000
with a key in here.

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:39.000
And

00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:41.000
now we have

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:43.000
post-processing

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:45.000
sparsity

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:47.000
tables. And I brought you a third

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:49.000
one because fleeting is fun, right?

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:51.000
And that

00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:53.000
third one

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:55.000
is better errors.

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:57.000
Not quite as big and flashy

00:42:57.000 --> 00:42:59.000
as the other topics,

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:01.000
but more like the bread and

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:03.000
butter of things.

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:05.000
And

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:07.000
sometimes

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:09.000
you notice.

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:11.000
Usually

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:13.000
when you run into an error,

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:15.000
it's not the best moment in your life.

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:17.000
And

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:19.000
recipes

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:21.000
used to be

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:23.000
pretty tricky.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:25.000
So you

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:27.000
write your beautiful recipe.

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:29.000
You try to fit your

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:31.000
workflow. You get an

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:33.000
error. You're like, okay, fine.

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:35.000
I know my debugging strategies. I'm going to

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:37.000
bake that data set. First,

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:39.000
I'm going to bake it.

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:41.000
Remove the complexity of the work.

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:43.000
And then you try to prep it

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:45.000
and you still get an error.

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:47.000
Hopefully the error

00:43:47.000 --> 00:43:49.000
tells you something useful. So here

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:51.000
it says a column already

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:53.000
compounds new level. So new level

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:55.000
is like, oh, yeah, I did something

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:57.000
and you can look for that

00:43:57.000 --> 00:43:59.000
step.

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:01.000
And

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:03.000
I know that people have been

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:05.000
devising a debugging

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:07.000
strategy where they'll comment in and

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:09.000
out of steps to

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:11.000
narrow it down. That is a good

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:13.000
strategy, but wouldn't

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:15.000
it be lovely if this thing just told

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:17.000
you which step the problem is at?

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:19.000
And that is

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:21.000
what it does now.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:23.000
And, you know, it's not a new

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:25.000
feature, although that one is so

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:27.000
helpful. You could somewhat argue

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:29.000
it's a new feature, but often

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:33.000
the error messages

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:35.000
are not the thing that you can

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:37.000
write

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:39.000
a lovely blog post about.

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:41.000
We do write about them, but they're sort of slotted

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:43.000
into things.

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:45.000
And I've decided

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:47.000
to

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:49.000
put a little bit of a

00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:51.000
variation on the keynote

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:53.000
topics then, usually.

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:55.000
So I have given you

00:44:55.000 --> 00:44:57.000
an exciting work in progress.

00:44:57.000 --> 00:44:59.000
But I also

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:01.000
want to talk about the other

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:03.000
work that we do.

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:05.000
And it doesn't always result

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:07.000
in extremely helpful

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:09.000
error changes

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:11.000
that you can change.

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:13.000
So this is a little bit of a

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:15.000
how we work

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:17.000
kind of section

00:45:17.000 --> 00:45:19.000
of this talk.

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:21.000
And we typically

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:23.000
call this type of work upkeep.

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:25.000
It is largely

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:27.000
the same as maintenance

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:29.000
work, but not

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:31.000
in the sense of somebody else changes their

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:33.000
package and breaks your manual

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:35.000
update stuff. That falls

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:37.000
into upkeep as well.

00:45:37.000 --> 00:45:39.000
But upkeep also

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:41.000
is the idea that we

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:43.000
make an effort

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:45.000
to regularly touch

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:47.000
our packages,

00:45:47.000 --> 00:45:49.000
because

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:51.000
we have quite

00:45:51.000 --> 00:45:53.000
a few of them, and sometimes

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:55.000
you don't do new feature work on it for

00:45:55.000 --> 00:45:57.000
two years, and then you get

00:45:57.000 --> 00:45:59.000
a bug report, and you're

00:45:59.000 --> 00:46:01.000
like, why did it fix that?

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:03.000
You open up the code base, and you're like, ooh,

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:05.000
we are doing things differently now.

00:46:05.000 --> 00:46:07.000
And it's just,

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:09.000
it's not because you wrote bad

00:46:09.000 --> 00:46:11.000
code in the past. It's just because

00:46:11.000 --> 00:46:13.000
the world around it has moved on.

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:15.000
And so

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:17.000
we try to touch things

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:19.000
regularly. And if you're writing your own

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:21.000
packages, you don't

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:23.000
have to look after

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:25.000
the amount of packages a week. You just have

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:27.000
to be busy and do a lot

00:46:27.000 --> 00:46:29.000
of different things. You also might

00:46:29.000 --> 00:46:31.000
not get to touch your package every

00:46:31.000 --> 00:46:33.000
week. So

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:35.000
the idea here is

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:37.000
to show you what kind of tools

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:39.000
we use to both

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:41.000
provide users

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:43.000
with helpful errors,

00:46:43.000 --> 00:46:45.000
and to do that in a way

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:47.000
that lets us still stay

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:49.000
on top of things, to not

00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:51.000
accumulate the biggest maintenance

00:46:51.000 --> 00:46:53.000
burden in all of this.

00:46:53.000 --> 00:46:55.000
So

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:57.000
I hope that's an interesting

00:46:57.000 --> 00:46:59.000
variation on the new inflection

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:01.000
and work in progress.

00:47:01.000 --> 00:47:03.000
So what makes

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:05.000
an error helpful?

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:07.000
And I think you do need

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:09.000
to tell your users what happened.

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:11.000
That's like the basic.

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:13.000
It'd be good to know

00:47:13.000 --> 00:47:15.000
where it happened.

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:17.000
And the hard question

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:19.000
is like,

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:21.000
why did it happen? And you can't always

00:47:21.000 --> 00:47:23.000
use it as an error message, but you

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:25.000
can sometimes be

00:47:25.000 --> 00:47:27.000
pointing them in the

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:29.000
right direction. And

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:31.000
sometimes you can

00:47:31.000 --> 00:47:33.000
also point them

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:35.000
even further in the right direction

00:47:35.000 --> 00:47:37.000
by giving them like

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:39.000
hints to further places to look at things,

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:41.000
or if it's like

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:43.000
a clearly typical mistake, you can

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:45.000
be like, did you mean to do this

00:47:45.000 --> 00:47:47.000
instead?

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:49.000
With moderation. Don't be

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:51.000
quick. But

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:53.000
sometimes that's helpful. So

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:55.000
how do we do that

00:47:55.000 --> 00:47:57.000
kind of stuff? And I do hope

00:47:57.000 --> 00:47:59.000
you can read some of it.

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:01.000
Otherwise, I'm going to be

00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:03.000
beating out a lot of holes.

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:05.000
How's that working?

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:07.000
Sort of? Okay, cool. Excellent.

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:09.000
So I brought in

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:11.000
a small function. I'm going to use

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:13.000
speed here so I can see this a bit

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:15.000
better.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:17.000
It has nothing to do with timing models.

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:19.000
This is just

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:21.000
not overload your brain with statistics.

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:23.000
This is just about when it's time to

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:25.000
water your plant. And

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:27.000
that plant should be straight.

00:48:27.000 --> 00:48:29.000
Otherwise, it's going to error.

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:31.000
Because all you do later is

00:48:31.000 --> 00:48:33.000
paste the string

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:35.000
into the text and be like,

00:48:35.000 --> 00:48:37.000
I'll get it. That plant doesn't

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:39.000
need to be watered yet. But you don't want to see

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:41.000
that plant. You want to see the specific

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:43.000
one.

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:45.000
But if you use

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:47.000
that with a number, it's

00:48:47.000 --> 00:48:49.000
going to error.

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:51.000
Plant must be a string.

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:53.000
Okay, fair. The thing we have

00:48:53.000 --> 00:48:55.000
done so far to

00:48:55.000 --> 00:48:57.000
try to be helpful is put

00:48:57.000 --> 00:48:59.000
backticks on this here.

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:01.000
Just to indicate that that's the argument.

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:03.000
And that's

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:05.000
the thing where you might want to pull up

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:07.000
this documentation and be like, what was that?

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:09.000
Why does this not work?

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:11.000
So that's very minimal

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:13.000
stuff, but it helps.

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:15.000
But as a maintainer,

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:17.000
you have to remember to put

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:19.000
those backticks there. And you have to

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:21.000
remember that backticks are the thing

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:23.000
how to format arguments.

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:25.000
Or...

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:27.000
Oh, I highlighted

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:29.000
this. Okay. Or...

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:31.000
you switch from an

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:33.000
R-line abort statement, which is our version

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:35.000
of, like, baseline stop.

00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:37.000
That's the thing

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:39.000
that throws a turn. You can

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:41.000
switch to CLI abort.

00:49:41.000 --> 00:49:43.000
And CLI does a

00:49:43.000 --> 00:49:45.000
lot of things. Here, it

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:47.000
just does the styling. Not that

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:49.000
exciting, especially if it's just a few

00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:51.000
backticks. But the point being,

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:53.000
these are all small changes

00:49:53.000 --> 00:49:55.000
and they add up.

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:57.000
I'm going to show you a few more things about what

00:49:57.000 --> 00:49:59.000
CLI can do.

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:01.000
But

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:03.000
amongst other things, it can do a lot of different

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:05.000
styling parts. And you just

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:07.000
have to remember

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:09.000
to put the right tag,

00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:11.000
which is often easier than you'll remember

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:13.000
to consistently apply format

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:15.000
yourself.

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:17.000
So the user list

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:19.000
doesn't change.

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:21.000
And that's a good thing.

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:23.000
This just makes your own life easier.

00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:27.000
And I said I'd show

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:29.000
some more things that CLI can do.

00:50:29.000 --> 00:50:31.000
I'm

00:50:31.000 --> 00:50:33.000
going to change that message

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:35.000
that you get if you

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:37.000
succeed.

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:39.000
What we do in here is

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:41.000
apply CLI

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:43.000
functions across the board, including CLI

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:45.000
abort. So we have, like,

00:50:45.000 --> 00:50:47.000
we're basically doing

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:49.000
string interpolation. We have our

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:51.000
string and then we inject

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:53.000
the value of class in there.

00:50:53.000 --> 00:50:55.000
And then we print it out and we are

00:50:55.000 --> 00:50:57.000
really good citizens and we're putting a new line

00:50:57.000 --> 00:50:59.000
at the end and we have to remember to write that

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:01.000
new line.

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:03.000
If you want to do the same with CLI,

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:05.000
you just use CLI

00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:07.000
text and

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:09.000
do string interpolation by

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:11.000
putting curly brackets in the value itself.

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:13.000
So that's kind of

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:15.000
like a matchup of

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:17.000
the glue package

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:19.000
and the Arlang abort.

00:51:19.000 --> 00:51:21.000
And then it does an additional thing

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:23.000
because

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:27.000
nothing keeps you from putting several

00:51:27.000 --> 00:51:29.000
plots in.

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:31.000
So it would be nice if that sentence

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:33.000
worked for all of them.

00:51:33.000 --> 00:51:35.000
So what this does is, like,

00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:37.000
it looks clever

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:39.000
enough to see that

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:41.000
plants

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:43.000
may have multiple values

00:51:43.000 --> 00:51:45.000
and if it has only

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:47.000
one, it uses the first option

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:49.000
here.

00:51:51.000 --> 00:51:53.000
It says that plant doesn't

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:55.000
have to be watered

00:51:55.000 --> 00:51:57.000
like here. I'll get it.

00:51:57.000 --> 00:51:59.000
The monstera doesn't have to be watered yet.

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:01.000
But if you put in

00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:03.000
a vector of plants,

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:05.000
it says, I'll get it. The monstera

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:07.000
and that other plant

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:09.000
don't need to be watered

00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:11.000
yet.

00:52:11.000 --> 00:52:13.000
This is not ground breaking.

00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:15.000
It's not

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:17.000
playing with math.

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:19.000
But it's pretty darn convenient.

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:21.000
You get to offer your users nice

00:52:21.000 --> 00:52:23.000
English sentences without

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:25.000
doing all the

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:27.000
figuring out

00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:29.000
whether it's plural or not and how that

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:31.000
pluralization should go and where it

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:33.000
pastes in all of the objects.

00:52:33.000 --> 00:52:35.000
That's

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:37.000
pretty nice if you do this

00:52:37.000 --> 00:52:39.000
a lot of times or if you

00:52:39.000 --> 00:52:41.000
only do it very sporadically.

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:43.000
Because if you're not touching that often, you might

00:52:43.000 --> 00:52:45.000
go through the trouble.

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:47.000
I feel like that is

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:49.000
a nice thing for someone who maintains

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:51.000
a package.

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:53.000
The result is a nice thank you

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:55.000
for someone who uses a package.

00:52:57.000 --> 00:52:59.000
I said there's a bunch more formatting

00:52:59.000 --> 00:53:01.000
options. The ones I use most regularly

00:53:01.000 --> 00:53:03.000
are the catch-all.

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:05.000
Format this as code.

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:07.000
Format this as

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:09.000
a class.

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:11.000
Format this one as a function.

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:13.000
If you just give it the function name,

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:15.000
it will add records and

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:17.000
pull out semantics.

00:53:17.000 --> 00:53:19.000
What's really cool is what happens

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:21.000
if you give it package name,

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:23.000
colon, colon,

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:25.000
function name.

00:53:25.000 --> 00:53:27.000
It creates

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:29.000
depending on which IDE you're in,

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:31.000
hyperlinks

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:33.000
to the documentation pages.

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:35.000
You get an error message that might say

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:37.000
look at this function.

00:53:37.000 --> 00:53:39.000
You click to get there.

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:43.000
Then you can do

00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:45.000
more jazz with links.

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:47.000
In Parsnip,

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:49.000
we sometimes want people to look up

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:51.000
the model

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:53.000
specification and the object is called

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:55.000
model for spec.

00:53:55.000 --> 00:53:57.000
That's okay,

00:53:57.000 --> 00:53:59.000
but sometimes we just want to say

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:01.000
model specification.

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:03.000
The error message

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:05.000
makes it so that if you click on

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:07.000
model specification, you land there.

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:11.000
If you're in quarter slides,

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:13.000
you're not in an interactive IDE.

00:54:13.000 --> 00:54:15.000
You don't get hyperlinks there,

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:17.000
but you get to see how

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:19.000
it looks if you're doing it

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:21.000
say on a console because

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:23.000
that's where you run your R.

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:25.000
Then it will add

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:27.000
the code that you

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:29.000
could run to get to the help page.

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:31.000
It doesn't leave you in

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:33.000
a bug if you don't have hyperlinks

00:54:33.000 --> 00:54:35.000
in your thing, but if you can

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:37.000
have them, it will give you hyperlinks.

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:41.000
That's a little bit of

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:43.000
CLI

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:45.000
niceness for

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:47.000
the error message.

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:49.000
The other thing that we're

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:51.000
changing throughout

00:54:51.000 --> 00:54:53.000
the framework is

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:55.000
to pay more attention

00:54:55.000 --> 00:54:57.000
to

00:54:57.000 --> 00:54:59.000
the kind of

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:01.000
call info that you get

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:03.000
when you use an error

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:05.000
because that tells you where.

00:55:05.000 --> 00:55:07.000
We have

00:55:07.000 --> 00:55:09.000
a bunch of functions that are internal.

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:11.000
They're not actually meant to be user

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:13.000
tracing.

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:15.000
We have others,

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:17.000
and then they call them, but

00:55:17.000 --> 00:55:19.000
what happens if you call

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:21.000
plant hair, which then in turns

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:23.000
calls time to water,

00:55:23.000 --> 00:55:25.000
is

00:55:25.000 --> 00:55:27.000
if it throws an error,

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:29.000
it will show error in time to water.

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:31.000
Here that sort of means something,

00:55:33.000 --> 00:55:35.000
but not all

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:37.000
internal functions are named

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:39.000
with the care that you do

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:41.000
for user-facing features.

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:43.000
Fact of life, I would say.

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:47.000
To then expose

00:55:47.000 --> 00:55:49.000
your user to your internals

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:51.000
in an environment where they are

00:55:51.000 --> 00:55:53.000
under great stress because they produced

00:55:53.000 --> 00:55:55.000
an error is maybe not the moment

00:55:55.000 --> 00:55:57.000
you want to do this.

00:55:57.000 --> 00:55:59.000
What we would like here

00:55:59.000 --> 00:56:01.000
is for that thing,

00:56:01.000 --> 00:56:03.000
if you call plant care

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:05.000
and it throws an error,

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:07.000
for it to say plant care

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:09.000
and not be like,

00:56:09.000 --> 00:56:11.000
tell your user to be like, sorry, where's that

00:56:11.000 --> 00:56:13.000
coming from?

00:56:13.000 --> 00:56:15.000
If they want to go jump into a debugger,

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:17.000
they still can if you're not keeping

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:19.000
them on it, but

00:56:19.000 --> 00:56:21.000
a casual user

00:56:21.000 --> 00:56:23.000
might get confused with this

00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:25.000
and you can hide it pretty easily.

00:56:27.000 --> 00:56:29.000
CLI abort

00:56:29.000 --> 00:56:31.000
has a

00:56:31.000 --> 00:56:33.000
call argument.

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:35.000
The nifty thing that happens here is that

00:56:35.000 --> 00:56:37.000
in the function definition,

00:56:37.000 --> 00:56:39.000
we say

00:56:39.000 --> 00:56:41.000
capture the calling environment

00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:45.000
and then pass that

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:47.000
to

00:56:47.000 --> 00:56:49.000
CLI abort.

00:56:49.000 --> 00:56:51.000
When you execute

00:56:51.000 --> 00:56:53.000
plant care

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:55.000
and then you execute time to water,

00:56:55.000 --> 00:56:57.000
time to water is

00:56:57.000 --> 00:56:59.000
where am I being called?

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:01.000
Oh, I'm being called in the

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:03.000
context of plant care.

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:05.000
Capture that and then when you error

00:57:05.000 --> 00:57:07.000
spit that one out.

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:09.000
So now you have the

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:11.000
user facing function as the function

00:57:11.000 --> 00:57:13.000
that throws the error.

00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:17.000
Also not

00:57:17.000 --> 00:57:19.000
the flashiest, do you think?

00:57:19.000 --> 00:57:21.000
But helpful.

00:57:21.000 --> 00:57:23.000
You will see these changes

00:57:23.000 --> 00:57:25.000
getting rolled out

00:57:25.000 --> 00:57:27.000
across time.

00:57:27.000 --> 00:57:29.000
We sure do have a lot of error times

00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:31.000
so it is taking us a while.

00:57:31.000 --> 00:57:33.000
We've been at it for a good bit

00:57:33.000 --> 00:57:35.000
but I think we've

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:37.000
halfway there.

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:39.000
Once all of these changes

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:41.000
have passed,

00:57:41.000 --> 00:57:43.000
we will get errors in this regard

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:45.000
as well.

00:57:45.000 --> 00:57:47.000
I am like

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:49.000
at time, am I not?

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:51.000
Should we think?

00:57:53.000 --> 00:57:55.000
I'm...

00:57:55.000 --> 00:57:57.000
Well, okay.

00:57:57.000 --> 00:57:59.000
I have two more

00:57:59.000 --> 00:58:01.000
things to show you.

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:03.000
Let's do them, right?

00:58:03.000 --> 00:58:05.000
You still awake?

00:58:05.000 --> 00:58:07.000
You're doing better with this time than me, actually.

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:09.000
Okay.

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:11.000
So we were like

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:13.000
what happened, where did it happen, and now we

00:58:13.000 --> 00:58:15.000
get into the meaty question of why.

00:58:15.000 --> 00:58:17.000
And

00:58:17.000 --> 00:58:19.000
this is sort of like back to the start

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:21.000
where we're moving the plant care

00:58:21.000 --> 00:58:23.000
where we're just like bare bones

00:58:23.000 --> 00:58:25.000
time to water.

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:27.000
It tells us it must be a

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:29.000
string. And it's good it tells

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:31.000
us what it must be

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:33.000
but sometimes they're like

00:58:33.000 --> 00:58:35.000
okay, fine, I get that part

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:37.000
but what was it

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:39.000
if it wasn't a string?

00:58:39.000 --> 00:58:41.000
I thought it would be a string.

00:58:41.000 --> 00:58:43.000
And that's a pretty

00:58:43.000 --> 00:58:45.000
easy way

00:58:45.000 --> 00:58:47.000
to add that information.

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:50.000
It doesn't always

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:52.000
save a user from having to

00:58:52.000 --> 00:58:54.000
go debug stuff more severely

00:58:54.000 --> 00:58:56.000
but it's a nice

00:58:56.000 --> 00:58:58.000
starting point

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:00.000
to get to something

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:02.000
like plant must be a string

00:59:02.000 --> 00:59:04.000
not a number.

00:59:04.000 --> 00:59:06.000
Where did the number come from?

00:59:06.000 --> 00:59:08.000
Well in this case you can see that but sometimes

00:59:08.000 --> 00:59:10.000
you're like

00:59:10.000 --> 00:59:12.000
hold on, why is it that?

00:59:12.000 --> 00:59:14.000
And the way to do this

00:59:14.000 --> 00:59:16.000
in CLI

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:18.000
is to stick fonts

00:59:18.000 --> 00:59:20.000
in curly brackets

00:59:20.000 --> 00:59:22.000
and then have it in the

00:59:22.000 --> 00:59:24.000
tag of

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:26.000
object type friendly. And what that thing

00:59:26.000 --> 00:59:28.000
does is

00:59:28.000 --> 00:59:30.000
evaluate what object type plant is

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:32.000
and then spit out

00:59:32.000 --> 00:59:34.000
a friendly English language

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:36.000
description of that.

00:59:36.000 --> 00:59:38.000
So 5

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:40.000
turns into a number

00:59:42.000 --> 00:59:44.000
and it works for a multitude

00:59:44.000 --> 00:59:46.000
of objects pretty broadly

00:59:46.000 --> 00:59:48.000
and my

00:59:48.000 --> 00:59:50.000
test to see how far I can stretch it

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:52.000
is to take

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:54.000
our basically hello world example

00:59:54.000 --> 00:59:56.000
of a linear model, so yes

00:59:56.000 --> 00:59:58.000
I put a linear model in the time to water function

00:59:58.000 --> 01:00:00.000
and it does tell me

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:02.000
it must be a string not an LM object.

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:04.000
Good.

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:08.000
So that's pretty

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:10.000
helpful and it doesn't

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:12.000
take much effort to add

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:14.000
that.

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:16.000
So that's

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:18.000
a little bit of nudging you

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:20.000
giving your user a first

01:00:20.000 --> 01:00:22.000
step on the path of like

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:24.000
why did it happen?

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:26.000
That doesn't always solve your problems but

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:28.000
it's a

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:30.000
relatively cheap and easy

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:32.000
way to get people

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:34.000
in the right direction.

01:00:36.000 --> 01:00:38.000
Sometimes you want to

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:40.000
be more explicit and have more stuff to say

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:42.000
about how to fix a particular

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:44.000
problem

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:46.000
and you want to put that hell into

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:48.000
the error message

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:50.000
but then if you have a lot to say

01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:52.000
you run the risk of producing

01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:54.000
an error message

01:00:54.000 --> 01:00:56.000
and then nobody will

01:00:56.000 --> 01:00:58.000
read your helpful text.

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:00.000
It's just a long text.

01:01:00.000 --> 01:01:02.000
But if you break it up a little bit

01:01:02.000 --> 01:01:04.000
and give people three bullet points

01:01:04.000 --> 01:01:06.000
your chance is much

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:08.000
better at reaching them.

01:01:08.000 --> 01:01:10.000
So what CLI

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:12.000
and RLA errors

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:14.000
can do is give you bulletisms

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:16.000
and that happens when

01:01:16.000 --> 01:01:18.000
you not just

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:20.000
give it a string

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:22.000
but rather a vector.

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:24.000
And then I say I equals

01:01:24.000 --> 01:01:26.000
and that's sort of like an

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:28.000
informational bullet point down here.

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:30.000
It still says error

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:32.000
in that function and then

01:01:32.000 --> 01:01:34.000
the error message, which I have changed

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:36.000
to switch things up at the last minute

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:38.000
and then it has like I

01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:40.000
and it gives another hint.

01:01:42.000 --> 01:01:44.000
And that is usually

01:01:44.000 --> 01:01:46.000
helpful if

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:48.000
you want to point people to other

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:50.000
functions. You use the linking of our

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:52.000
shoulder. So where we

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:54.000
do this for real and not just like

01:01:54.000 --> 01:01:56.000
picture parts,

01:01:56.000 --> 01:01:58.000
you will see when you need to audit them,

01:01:58.000 --> 01:02:00.000
is

01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:08.000
a situation where this is helpful

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:10.000
is if you're expecting data

01:02:10.000 --> 01:02:12.000
in a particular format,

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:14.000
say spatial data,

01:02:14.000 --> 01:02:16.000
and you can leave a hint

01:02:16.000 --> 01:02:18.000
of saying, right,

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:20.000
look at the help page of this particular

01:02:20.000 --> 01:02:22.000
function to convert your object

01:02:22.000 --> 01:02:24.000
from a regular data frame

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:26.000
to an SF object or something else.

01:02:28.000 --> 01:02:30.000
We sometimes point to

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:32.000
other functions in the time

01:02:32.000 --> 01:02:34.000
models ecosystem for

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:36.000
this.

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:40.000
Time to wrap it up.

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:42.000
I think

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:44.000
errors are most

01:02:44.000 --> 01:02:46.000
helpful if they tell you what happened.

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:48.000
That's the error message itself

01:02:48.000 --> 01:02:50.000
and CLI

01:02:50.000 --> 01:02:52.000
has a bunch of options for you to add,

01:02:52.000 --> 01:02:54.000
style in, string interpolation,

01:02:54.000 --> 01:02:56.000
pluralization, links

01:02:56.000 --> 01:02:58.000
and all of that jazz.

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:00.000
It can help

01:03:00.000 --> 01:03:02.000
you be more direct

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:04.000
where an error happened.

01:03:04.000 --> 01:03:06.000
You don't always

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:08.000
have to make it

01:03:08.000 --> 01:03:10.000
just a user-facing one.

01:03:10.000 --> 01:03:12.000
If your function does call out

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:14.000
different things and you

01:03:14.000 --> 01:03:16.000
think it is helpful to know

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:18.000
where, we're not going

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:20.000
to say, oh, it's error in

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:22.000
tune rig, but that's a non-server

01:03:22.000 --> 01:03:24.000
function and sometimes it might be helpful

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:26.000
to know if that was a pre-processing error

01:03:26.000 --> 01:03:28.000
or a model fitting error or something else.

01:03:28.000 --> 01:03:30.000
But it gives

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:32.000
you the control to

01:03:32.000 --> 01:03:34.000
say the level of

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:36.000
abstraction that you're going to

01:03:36.000 --> 01:03:38.000
give here and which call is going to show

01:03:38.000 --> 01:03:40.000
up.

01:03:40.000 --> 01:03:42.000
The

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:44.000
driving question of why does this happen?

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:46.000
You can help people

01:03:46.000 --> 01:03:48.000
by not only telling them what

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:50.000
was supposed to happen, but also

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:52.000
what actually did happen.

01:03:52.000 --> 01:03:54.000
So that was

01:03:54.000 --> 01:03:56.000
impartial, object-friendly

01:03:56.000 --> 01:03:58.000
and if you

01:03:58.000 --> 01:04:00.000
have any helpful hints

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:02.000
to tell people, you

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:04.000
can add that on informational

01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:06.000
messages or other types.

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:08.000
There's a bit more styling in what

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:10.000
the bullet points look like.

01:04:10.000 --> 01:04:12.000
But essentially, break up your text,

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:14.000
add some more context

01:04:14.000 --> 01:04:16.000
if you think it will be helpful.

01:04:16.000 --> 01:04:18.000
And

01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:20.000
to

01:04:20.000 --> 01:04:22.000
my last slide,

01:04:22.000 --> 01:04:24.000
what if you want to know the news and I'm not there

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:26.000
to talk to you for an hour.

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:28.000
Announcements about

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:30.000
new things go on to the

01:04:30.000 --> 01:04:32.000
tidyverbs blog at tidyverbs.org

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:34.000
slash blogs.

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:36.000
And then our column on the web is

01:04:36.000 --> 01:04:38.000
tidybubbles.org where we

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:40.000
have a collection of articles

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:42.000
that are more in-depth

01:04:42.000 --> 01:04:44.000
texts about various topics

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:46.000
of statistics and modeling

01:04:46.000 --> 01:04:48.000
and what you might want to know

01:04:48.000 --> 01:04:50.000
about that in the context of

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:52.000
tidybubbles.

01:04:52.000 --> 01:04:54.000
And with that,

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:56.000
thank you for your attention.

01:05:16.000 --> 01:05:18.000
Thank you very much.

