01:12:26.000 --> 01:12:28.000
It depends on like

01:12:28.000 --> 01:12:30.000
what your context is. If all the

01:12:30.000 --> 01:12:32.000
people around you are computer scientists

01:12:32.000 --> 01:12:34.000
or general software engineers

01:12:34.000 --> 01:12:36.000
and they don't know

01:12:36.000 --> 01:12:38.000
what to do with R, that is hard

01:12:38.000 --> 01:12:40.000
but not because of how R is, but because

01:12:40.000 --> 01:12:42.000
of the context. And if they

01:12:42.000 --> 01:12:44.000
are like, no, please use

01:12:44.000 --> 01:12:46.000
a general purpose language like Python,

01:12:46.000 --> 01:12:48.000
then that's a learning

01:12:48.000 --> 01:12:50.000
center. Do that.

01:12:50.000 --> 01:12:52.000
But it's nothing about R per se that

01:12:52.000 --> 01:12:54.000
keeps you from it.

01:12:54.000 --> 01:12:56.000
And

01:12:56.000 --> 01:12:58.000
in the spirit of sharing

01:12:58.000 --> 01:13:00.000
work in progress, the topic

01:13:00.000 --> 01:13:02.000
